<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Manual"><PMID Version="1">2378759</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>1990</Year><Month>09</Month><Day>10</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2018</Year><Month>11</Month><Day>30</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Print">1130-0108</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Print"><Volume>77</Volume><Issue>3</Issue><PubDate><Year>1990</Year><Month>Mar</Month></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Revista espanola de enfermedades digestivas</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Rev Esp Enferm Dig</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>[Changes in pancreatic secretion in alcoholic liver disease].</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>197</StartPage><EndPage>204</EndPage><MedlinePgn>197-204</MedlinePgn></Pagination><Abstract><AbstractText>By means of consecutive pancreatic stimulation, we have investigated the presence of changes of pancreatic function in alcoholic patients, with and without alcoholic liver disease, in order to detect functional alterations and possible association of hepatic and pancreatic disease. The patients were 49 chronic alcoholics (8 patients without liver disease, 11 hepatic steatosis, 9 alcoholic hepatitis and 21 alcoholic cirrhosis) and 15 non alcoholic subjects (8 normal controls and 7 cases of non alcoholic cirrhosis). In all the cases two consecutive stimulations were carried out: first with secretin and cholecystokinin (CCK) and second with CCK alone. The total volume and concentration as well as the output of bicarbonate, trypsin, amylase and total proteins were measured in the duodenal juice. Patients with alcoholic cirrhosis had larger volumes of duodenal juice and lower concentrations of bicarbonate, enzymes and proteins. There was also a tendency to larger volume and lower bicarbonate concentration as the hepatic lesion was more severe. Bicarbonate output was significatively higher in patients with alcoholic cirrhosis but for the remaining parameters the outputs were similar in all the groups. In conclusion, the alterations in pancreatic function parallel the severity of the liver disease. None of the patients had changes consistent with chronic pancreatitis.</AbstractText></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Del Olmo Mart&#xed;nez</LastName><ForeName>M L</ForeName><Initials>ML</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Servicio de Gastroenterol&#xf3;g&#xed;a, Hospital Ram&#xf3;n y Cajal, Madrid.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Barba Bermejo</LastName><ForeName>M</ForeName><Initials>M</Initials></Author></AuthorList><Language>spa</Language><PublicationTypeList><PublicationType UI="D016428">Journal Article</PublicationType></PublicationTypeList><VernacularTitle>Modificaciones de la secreci&#xf3;n pancre&#xe1;tica en la enfermedad hep&#xe1;tica alcoh&#xf3;lica.</VernacularTitle></Article><MedlineJournalInfo><Country>Spain</Country><MedlineTA>Rev Esp Enferm Dig</MedlineTA><NlmUniqueID>9007566</NlmUniqueID><ISSNLinking>1130-0108</ISSNLinking></MedlineJournalInfo><ChemicalList><Chemical><RegistryNumber>1393-25-5</RegistryNumber><NameOfSubstance UI="D012633">Secretin</NameOfSubstance></Chemical><Chemical><RegistryNumber>9011-97-6</RegistryNumber><NameOfSubstance UI="D002766">Cholecystokinin</NameOfSubstance></Chemical></ChemicalList><CitationSubset>IM</CitationSubset><MeshHeadingList><MeshHeading><DescriptorName UI="D000328" MajorTopicYN="N">Adult</DescriptorName></MeshHeading><MeshHeading><DescriptorName UI="D000368" MajorTopicYN="N">Aged</DescriptorName></MeshHeading><MeshHeading><DescriptorName UI="D002766" MajorTopicYN="N">Cholecystokinin</DescriptorName></MeshHeading><MeshHeading><DescriptorName UI="D004386" MajorTopicYN="N">Duodenum</DescriptorName></MeshHeading><MeshHeading><DescriptorName UI="D005766" MajorTopicYN="N">Gastrointestinal Contents</DescriptorName><QualifierName UI="Q000032" MajorTopicYN="N">analysis</QualifierName></MeshHeading><MeshHeading